      {
        "id": 4020160,
        "name": "Guillermo M e n a",
        "username": "Guillermo_M",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/guillermo_m/{size}/3751_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-03-01T15:15:20.310Z",
        "cooked": "<p>It could be an awkward phase as <a class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/william_kelley\">@William_Kelley</a> says and just need more time in bottle, as <a class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/vladb\">@VladB</a> says. Thanks both for the comments.</p>\n<p>Like I said, I still have high hopes. If I had noticed the difference in ABVs, I probably would have opened the 2020 Volnay as my first look at his reds. I\u2019ll probably do that soon.</p>\n<p>This is a producer I <em>want</em> to like (just like I <em>want</em> to like Cyril Audoin and for the same reasons) because the pricing has been reasonable and the winemaking genuine. But, style is style.</p>\n<p>My plan was to age Javillier\u2019s 2019 and 2020 1er crus for a while (Volnay Caillerets or Clos des Ch\u00eanes or Pommard Rugiens), but I do want to figure out if I want to buy more from him as vintages progress. So if that 2020 Volnay doesn\u2019t convince me, I\u2019ll be facing a difficult choice.</p>",
